<text>   
 An Introduction to Light-Matter Interactions

Originally by Concord Staff, modified by Ed O&apos;Sullivan, Parkland College

Light-matter interactions are important, not only because the science of light plays a leading role in the current waves of technological innovations, but also because they provide insights for us to understand the regions of outer and inner space that are beyond our intuition. At the macroscopic level, light travels so fast that it is possible for us to learn about what has happened in stars light years away from the Earth. At the microscopic level, light can be used as probes to detect what is going on among atoms and molecules, and as &quot;smart fingers&quot; to manipulate microstructures. The knowledge of light-matter interactions is necessary to understanding many basic concepts in the state-of-the-art technologies.  This activity will begin by introducing the basic concepts on light followed by several simulations which model the interactions between light and matter.

 

1: Introducing light and photons
2. The Electromagnetic Spectrum
3: Photon absorption and emission I
4: Photon absorption and emission II
5: Different Substances Have Different Photon Absorptions and Emissions
6: Light can heat matter
7: Simulating black color
8: Heated matter can emit light

 

